'''2,4,5-Trihydroxyamphetamine''' ('''THM''') is a [[neurotoxin]] and a metabolite of [[MDMA]]. It comes from the ring-hydroxylation of [[3,4-Methylenedioxyamphetamine|3,4-methylenedioxyamphetamine]] (MDA).

In one paper, it was shown to reduce hippocampal [[tryptophan hydroxylase]] activity by 54% after short-term treatment.<ref name="MyUser_Ncbi.nlm.nih.gov_July_8_2015c">{{cite journal |title= Short-term effects of 2,4,5-trihydroxyamphetamine, 2,4,5-trihydroxymethamphetamine and 3,4-dihydroxymethamphetamine on central tryptophan hydroxylase activity.| pmid=8496826 | volume=265 | issue=2 | date=May 1993 | journal=J Pharmacol Exp Ther | pages=813–8}}</ref> In another study, it was shown to significantly reduce striatal [[tyrosine hydroxylase]] activity.<ref>{{cite journal | journal = J Pharmacol Exp Ther | date = 1993 | volume = 265 | issue = 2 | pages = 813–818 | title = Short-term effects of 2,4,5-trihydroxyamphetamine, 2,4,5-trihydroxymethamphetamine and 3,4-dihydroxymethamphetamine on central tryptophan hydroxyls activity |vauthors=Elayan I, Gibb JW, Hanson GR, Lim HK, Foltz RL, Johnson M | pmid= 8496826}}</ref>

