{{refimprove|date=April 2013}} [[File:PadredePPK.jpg|thumb|Max Hans Kuczynski]]
'''Maxime Hans Kuczyński''' (2 February 1890 – 1967) was a Polish-Peruvian physician.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hsozkult.geschichte.hu-berlin.de/termine/id=6285|title=Social medicine, medical geography and health care for indigenous peoples: "Ethnic Pathology" (Max Kuczynski, 1925) in Germany, Russia, Latin America and beyond|website=Hsozkult.geschichte.hu-berlin.de|accessdate=28 July 2012}}</ref>
==Biography== Maxime Kuczyński was born near [[Poznań]], then in the [[Province of Posen]] within the [[German Empire]], as the son of Emma (''[[Given name#Name at birth|née]]'' Schlesinger) and Louis Kuczyński, both of Jewish origin.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wiadomosci.onet.pl/swiat/wybory-w-peru-kuczynski-prowadzi-ale-czesc-kart-trzeba-sprawdzic/dq6ekx|title=Wybory w Peru: Kuczynski prowadzi, ale część kart trzeba sprawdzić|date=9 June 2016|website=Wiadomosci.onet.pl|accessdate=14 October 2017}}</ref> The family moved to [[Berlin]] shortly after his birth. He studied [[medicine]] and [[natural science]] at the [[University of Rostock]]. In 1913 he received his degree in [[philosophy]], and in 1919 a degree in [[medicine]].<ref>Max Hans Kuczynski: ''Untersuchungen an Trichomonaden''. In: ''Archiv für [[Protisten|Protistenkunde]]'', Fischer, Jena, Bd. 33 (1914), S. 119–204.</ref>
During [[World War I]], he served in the German army and participated in the [[Balkans Campaign (World War I)|Balkans Campaign]]. In 1924, he received his professorship. After the Nazis came to power he fled to Peru.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/peru-leading-presidential-contender-is-son-of-polish-jews-who-fled-nazis/|title=Peru presidential contender is son of Polish Jews who fled Nazis|website=Timesofisrael.com|accessdate=14 October 2017}}</ref> Between 1924 and 1926 he conducted [[Anthropology|anthropological]] research in [[Central Asia]], and later, between 1938 and 1948, in [[Andes]].<ref>Lawrence K. Altman: ''Who Goes First? The Story of Self-Experimentation in Medicine''. University of California Press, Berkeley 1987, {{ISBN|0-520-21281-9}}, S. 4.</ref><ref>Albert Erhardt: ''Infektionen'', Bd. I (= Ergänzungswerk zum ''Handbuch der experimentellen Pharmakologie'', begründet von [[Arthur Heffter]], herausgegeben von [[Oskar Eichler]], Bd. 16: ''Erzeugung von Krankheitszuständen durch das Experiment'', Teil 9). Springer, Berlin 1964, S. 118.</ref><ref>Marcos Cueto: ''Un médico alemán en los Andes: La visión médico-social de Maxime Kuczynski-Godard''. In: ''Allpanchis'', Jg. 32 (2000), Themenheft 56: ''Sanos, enfermos y salvos?'', S. 39–74.</ref>
Kuczyński died in [[Lima]].
His son, [[Pedro Pablo Kuczynski]], born in Lima in 1938, was [[Prime Minister of Peru|Prime Minister]] between 2005 and 2006. A decade later, he became [[President of Peru|President]] after winning the [[Peruvian general election, 2016|second round in June 2016]]. His American granddaughter, [[Alex Kuczynski]], is a journalist and writer.{{cn|date=October 2017}}
